>\r\n<br>\r\nSo the low density of information in \u0022Amazing Fantastic Incredible\u0022 makes it a fast and entertaining read, but frustrating for someone who wants to understand Lee\u0027s career path and how it evolved with changes in the comics business over all those decades. Any life has its ups and downs, but he tends to note his downs with just a single panel with a sad Stan saying \u0022the less said about that, the better.\u0022 Maybe for Stan, that\u0027s true. For me as a reader, I feel like all of the interesting stuff was left behind the curtain.<br>\r\n<br>\r\nStill, the art is great, and it leans on the comics medium to show instead of tell. As a way for Stan Lee to take a joyful victory lap near the end of his epic career, saying \u0022and this cool thing happened, and THIS thing, and THIS!\u0022 it\u0027s a pretty fun little romp. He\u0027s a guy who has accomplished an awful lot, and you can\u0027t help smiling with him as he looks back on it all.<br>\r\n<br>\r\n<center>\r\n<a  href=\u0022http:\/\/www.amazon.com\/gp\/product\/1501107720\/ref=as_li_tl?ie=UTF8&camp=1789&creative=9325&creativeASIN=1501107720&linkCode=as2&tag=erfworld-20&linkId=5QHH3H72EEDTZEP6\u0022><img border=\u00220\u0022 src=\u0022http:\/\/ws-na.amazon-adsystem.com\/widgets\/q?_encoding=UTF8&ASIN=1501107720&Format=_SL110_&ID=AsinImage&MarketPlace=US&ServiceVersion=20070822&WS=1&tag=erfworld-20\u0022 ><\/a><img src=\u0022http:\/\/ir-na.amazon-adsystem.com\/e\/ir?t=erfworld-20&l=as2&o=1&a=1501107720\u0022 width=\u00221\u0022 height=\u00221\u0022 border=\u00220\u0022 alt=\u0022\u0022 style=\u0022border:none !important; margin:0px !important;\u0022 \/>\r\n<\/br>\r\n<br>\r\n<a href=http:\/\/forums.erfworld.com\/viewtopic.php?f=19&t=7082>What book should Rob read next?<\/a>\r\n<\/div><br \/><a href=\u0022http:\/\/www.erfworld.com\/mod\/contactform\/index.php\u0022 class=\u0022ad_report_button\u0022>Report autoplaying audio or other bad ad.<\/a>","guid":44987},{"title":"Erfworld Amazo